<BaseLayout title="Act Five" active="guide" description="Macbeth Act Five guide: Lady Macbeth's sleepwalking, Macbeth's nihilism and the tomorrow speech, the fulfilment of the prophecies and the restoration of order, with scene summaries, analysis of form and structure, and verified quotations for the coursework.">
  <div class="part-head">
    <div class="wrap">
      <p class="kicker">The Guide &middot; Act Five</p>
      <h1>The reckoning</h1>
      <p class="lede prose">
        Everything comes due. Lady Macbeth&rsquo;s buried guilt surfaces in her sleep; Macbeth
        faces an army and a grief that empty him of meaning; and the prophecies he trusted turn,
        one by one, into the instruments of his death. Act Five is short, fast and merciless, and
        it ends by putting the world back the right way up.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <section class="band">
    <div class="wrap prose">
      <h2 style="margin-top:0;">What happens</h2>
      <p>
        <strong>Scene 1 (Dunsinane, a room in the castle).</strong> A doctor and a waiting
        gentlewoman watch Lady Macbeth walk and talk in her sleep. Candle in hand, she rubs at
        a spot of blood only she can see, murmuring fragments of the murders she once dismissed:
        Duncan&rsquo;s death, Banquo, Lady Macduff. The woman who told her husband a little water
        would clear them of the deed now cannot wash her hands clean. The doctor concludes that
        her sickness is beyond medicine and needs a priest, not a physician.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Scenes 2 to 8 (the country near Dunsinane, the castle, Birnam Wood, the field:
        the battle sequence).</strong> The play now cuts rapidly between the closing army and the
        cornered king. The Scottish lords march to meet the English force at Birnam, speaking of a
        tyrant whose stolen title hangs on him like a giant&rsquo;s robes on a thief (5.2). At
        Dunsinane, Macbeth swings between rage and despair, clinging to the prophecy that no man
        of woman born can hurt him while admitting his life has withered into the dry leaves of
        autumn (5.3). Malcolm orders every soldier to cut a bough from Birnam Wood for cover, and
        the forest begins, impossibly, to move (5.4). Word reaches Macbeth that his wife is dead;
        he answers with the &lsquo;tomorrow&rsquo; speech, and then a messenger reports the wood
        advancing (5.5). The army throws down its branches and attacks (5.6). Macbeth, still
        trusting the words that no natural-born man can kill him, cuts down young Siward (5.7).
        Then Macduff finds him, reveals he was &lsquo;from his mother&rsquo;s womb untimely
        ripped&rsquo;, and kills him (5.8).
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Scene 9 (within the castle).</strong> The victors gather. Old Siward hears that
        his son died facing his wounds and calls it a good death. Macduff enters carrying
        Macbeth&rsquo;s head and hails Malcolm as king. Malcolm rewards his followers with new
        titles, invites the exiles home, names Macbeth and his queen &lsquo;this dead butcher and
        his fiend-like queen&rsquo;, and prepares to be crowned at Scone. The order Macbeth
        overturned is restored, and the rightful line resumes.
      </p>

      <h2>A closer look</h2>
      <h3>Lady Macbeth&rsquo;s disintegration</h3>
      <p>
        The most powerful woman in the play unravels in her sleep, and Shakespeare marks the
        collapse through form. Lady Macbeth has spoken in commanding verse throughout; here she
        breaks into broken prose, the medium of the disordered and the low, her sentences reduced
        to fragments a stranger writes down. The imagery turns everything she once used against
        her husband back onto herself. She mocked him for fearing a &lsquo;little water&rsquo;;
        now she wails that &lsquo;all the perfumes of Arabia will not sweeten this little
        hand&rsquo;. She dismissed guilt as childish; now she cannot put down the candle, because
        the dark she summoned has become unbearable. Her flat, hopeless &lsquo;What&rsquo;s done
        cannot be undone&rsquo; echoes her own earlier counsel that what is done is done, and
        exposes it as a lie. The doctor&rsquo;s verdict, that she needs &lsquo;the divine&rsquo;
        rather than a physician, tells us her wound is moral, not medical. It is a quietly
        devastating fall: the schemer who thought she could control conscience is destroyed by it
        off stage, unseen, her death barely a line.
      </p>
      <h3>Macbeth&rsquo;s nihilism and the &lsquo;tomorrow&rsquo; speech</h3>
      <p>
        Macbeth&rsquo;s tragedy ends not in remorse but in emptiness. By Scene 5 he has, in his
        own words, almost forgotten the taste of fears; horror has become his climate, and he
        feels nothing at the shriek of women in the night. Then he is told his wife is dead, and
        the reply is the bleakest speech in the tragedy. &lsquo;She should have died
        hereafter&rsquo; is either grief or indifference, and the ambiguity is the point: he can
        no longer tell. What follows converts private loss into a vision of universal
        meaninglessness. Life is &lsquo;out, out, brief candle&rsquo;, a light snuffed to
        nothing; a strutting player forgotten the moment he leaves the stage; &lsquo;a tale told
        by an idiot, full of sound and fury, signifying nothing&rsquo;. The theatrical images are
        pointed in a play performed on a stage: Macbeth sees existence itself as a bad
        performance without an author. This is the endpoint of ambition unhooked from meaning.
        Having killed for a future, he arrives at a present in which nothing means anything, and
        can only say he begins &lsquo;to be aweary of the sun&rsquo;.
      </p>
      <h3>Form and structure: the prophecies close, the order returns</h3>
      <p>
        Act Five is engineered as a series of springing traps. Shakespeare planted each prophecy
        in Act Four so that it could be sprung here, and the pleasure and terror of the act lie in
        watching the reassurances Macbeth trusted turn into the exact means of his death. Birnam
        Wood cannot move, until soldiers carry it; no man of woman born can harm him, until a man
        cut untimely from his mother stands in front of him. The equivocation that comforted him
        now kills him, and the audience, who understood the trap all along, watches it shut. The
        battle scenes are deliberately brief and broken, a rush of short encounters that mirror a
        collapsing reign and hurry the play to its close. Structurally the act completes a great
        circle: it opens, like the whole play, with a report of a battle, but this time Macbeth is
        the enemy the loyal soldiers march against, and the head displayed at the end answers the
        traitor&rsquo;s head fixed on the battlements in Act One. The restoration is careful and
        conservative. Malcolm hands out titles, recalls the exiles, and looks to his coronation at
        Scone, and the natural order, the Great Chain that murder broke, is knitted back together.
        Even Macbeth&rsquo;s death honours the tragic form: he refuses to yield and dies fighting,
        recovering, at the very end, a soldier&rsquo;s courage the play cannot quite deny him.
      </p>

      <h2>Key quotations</h2>
      <table class="quote-table">
        <thead><tr><th>Quotation</th><th>Method</th><th>Why it matters</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td class="q">&lsquo;Out, damned spot! out, I say!&rsquo; (Act 5, Scene 1)</td>
            <td class="m">Imperative, prose, symbolism</td>
            <td>The blood she once washed off in seconds is now permanent and invisible. Guilt has moved inside, where no water reaches.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="q">&lsquo;All the perfumes of Arabia will not sweeten this little hand&rsquo; (Act 5, Scene 1)</td>
            <td class="m">Hyperbole, sensory imagery</td>
            <td>The scale of her guilt in a single image: nothing on earth can cover it. &lsquo;Little&rsquo; makes her suddenly small and human.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="q">&lsquo;What&rsquo;s done cannot be undone&rsquo; (Act 5, Scene 1)</td>
            <td class="m">Echo, dramatic irony</td>
            <td>Her old comfort that what is done is done, returned as a life sentence. The counsel she gave her husband now condemns her.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="q">&lsquo;giant&rsquo;s robes upon a dwarfish thief&rsquo; (Act 5, Scene 2)</td>
            <td class="m">Simile, clothing imagery</td>
            <td>The stolen crown never fits the usurper. The recurring motif of ill-fitting garments judges Macbeth&rsquo;s kingship as theft.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="q">&lsquo;my way of life is fall&rsquo;n into the sere, the yellow leaf&rsquo; (Act 5, Scene 3)</td>
            <td class="m">Metaphor, natural imagery</td>
            <td>Macbeth pictures his life as barren autumn: no honour, love or friends. Even he now sees what his ambition has cost him.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="q">&lsquo;She should have died hereafter&rsquo; (Act 5, Scene 5)</td>
            <td class="m">Ambiguity, understatement</td>
            <td>Grief or indifference, and Macbeth can no longer tell which. His response to his wife&rsquo;s death is a speech about nothing meaning anything.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="q">&lsquo;a tale told by an idiot, full of sound and fury, signifying nothing&rsquo; (Act 5, Scene 5)</td>
            <td class="m">Metaphor, metatheatre</td>
            <td>The nihilist&rsquo;s creed: life as meaningless performance. Ambition detached from meaning arrives, at last, at emptiness.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="q">&lsquo;from his mother&rsquo;s womb untimely ripped&rsquo; (Act 5, Scene 8)</td>
            <td class="m">Equivocation fulfilled, dramatic irony</td>
            <td>The prophecy that promised safety springs shut. The words Macbeth trusted become the exact instrument of his death.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="q">&lsquo;this dead butcher and his fiend-like queen&rsquo; (Act 5, Scene 9)</td>
            <td class="m">Epithet, framing</td>
            <td>The restored order&rsquo;s verdict, and its shaping of memory. The play&rsquo;s last word on the pair is one the audience is invited to weigh, not simply accept.</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <div class="box think">
        <h3>Think it through</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Lady Macbeth speaks in prose here, having spoken in verse before. What does that shift alone tell an audience about her state?</li>
          <li>Is &lsquo;tomorrow, and tomorrow, and tomorrow&rsquo; a moment of tragic insight or a final loss of feeling? Can it be both at once?</li>
          <li>Malcolm calls Lady Macbeth &lsquo;fiend-like&rsquo;. Having watched Scene 1, do you accept that as the play&rsquo;s judgement, or does the sleepwalking scene complicate it?</li>
          <li>Macbeth dies fighting rather than yielding. Does that final courage recover any of our sympathy, and should a tragedy want it to?</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="box exam">
        <h3>Towards the coursework</h3>
        <p>
          Act Five brings every argument home. For <strong>kingship</strong>, the ending stages
          the restoration of legitimate rule: Malcolm&rsquo;s ordered rewards and coronation at
          Scone answer the disorder Macbeth unleashed, and make the play&rsquo;s politics explicit
          for its royal first audience. For the <strong>presentation of women</strong>, the
          sleepwalking scene is the essay&rsquo;s richest evidence, a chance to argue whether the
          play punishes Lady Macbeth, pities her, or both, and whether &lsquo;fiend-like&rsquo; is
          fair. For <strong>masculinity</strong>, weigh Macbeth&rsquo;s final, doomed courage
          against the emptiness it now serves, and ask what the play thinks manly valour is worth
          in a bad cause. <strong>Writing task:</strong> in one paragraph, argue how far the ending
          restores moral order, opening with the context of the Great Chain of Being and looping
          back to it through the imagery of the final scene. Then take the whole essay forward on
          the <a href="/coursework/">coursework page</a>.
        </p>
      </div>

